Sequences of Arbitrages

Victor Kozyakin Institute for Information Transmission Problems, Moscow, Russia    Brian O’Callaghan University College Cork, Ireland    Alexei Pokrovskii University College Cork, Ireland
Abstract

The goal of this article is to understand some interesting features of sequences of arbitrage operations, which look relevant to various processes in Economics and Finances.

In the second part of the paper, analysis of sequences of arbitrages is reformulated in the linear algebra terms. This admits an elegant geometric interpretation of the problems under consideration linked to the asynchronous systems theory. We feel that this interpretation will be useful in understanding more complicated, and more realistic, mathematical models in economics.

MSC 2000: 91B26, 91B54, 91B64, 15A60

Key words and phrases: Economy models, sequences of arbitrages, matrix products, asynchronous systems

1 Motivation

Consider a mini-economy that involves only three producers. Each producer produces one of three goods: either Food, or Arms, or Medicine. The economical activity is reduced to the following three pair-wise barter operations:

F​o​o​d⇆A​r​m​s,F​o​o​d⇄M​e​d​i​c​i​n​e,A​r​m​s⇄M​e​d​i​c​i​n​e.formulae-sequence⇆𝐹𝑜𝑜𝑑𝐴𝑟𝑚𝑠formulae-sequence⇄𝐹𝑜𝑜𝑑𝑀𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑒⇄𝐴𝑟𝑚𝑠𝑀𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑒Food\leftrightarrows Arms,\quad Food\rightleftarrows Medicine,\quad Arms\rightleftarrows Medicine.

Suppose that the goods that are produced by each producer are measured in some units, and the corresponding (strictly positive) exchange rates, rF,Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{F,A}, rF​Msubscript𝑟𝐹𝑀r_{FM}, rA​Msubscript𝑟𝐴𝑀r_{AM}, are well defined. That is, one unit of Food can be exchanged for rF,Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{F,A} units of Arms. The rates related to the inverted arrows are reciprocal:

We treat the triplet

as the ensemble of principal exchange rates.

We suppose that, prior to a reference time moment 00, each producer knows only its own exchange rates: Food Producer does not know the value of rA​Msubscript𝑟𝐴𝑀r_{AM}, Arms Producer is unaware of rF​Msubscript𝑟𝐹𝑀r_{FM}, and Medicine Producer is unaware of rF​Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{FA}. We are interested in the case when the initial rates are unbalanced in the following sense. By assumption, Food Producer can exchange one unit of Food for rF​Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{FA} units of Arms. Let us suppose that unbeknownst to him the exchange rate between Medicine Producer and Arms Producer is such that the Food Producer could make a profit by first exchanging one unit of Food for rF​Msubscript𝑟𝐹𝑀r_{FM} units of Medicine and then exchanging these for Arms. Our motivation to proceed with this project was to understand possible scenarios of evolution of a similar mini-economy with four producers.

2 Economical Aspects

2.1 FARM-economy

Consider the economy “FARM” that includes four producers, which produce Food, Arms, Rellics and Medicine. The economical activity is described by six pair-wise barter operations:

F​o​o​d⇆A​r​m​s,F​o​o​d⇄R​e​l​i​c​s,F​o​o​d⇄M​e​d​i​c​i​n​e,A​r​m​s⇄R​e​l​i​c​s,A​r​m​s⇄M​e​d​i​c​i​n​e,R​e​l​i​c​s⇄M​e​d​i​c​i​n​e.⇆𝐹𝑜𝑜𝑑𝐴𝑟𝑚𝑠⇄𝐹𝑜𝑜𝑑𝑅𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑐𝑠⇄𝐹𝑜𝑜𝑑𝑀𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑒⇄𝐴𝑟𝑚𝑠𝑅𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑐𝑠⇄𝐴𝑟𝑚𝑠𝑀𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑒⇄𝑅𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑐𝑠𝑀𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑒\begin{array}[]{ccc}Food\leftrightarrows Arms,&Food\rightleftarrows Relics,&Food\rightleftarrows Medicine,\\ Arms\rightleftarrows Relics,&Arms\rightleftarrows Medicine,&Relics\rightleftarrows Medicine.\end{array}

The goods that are produced by each producer are measured in some units, and the exchange rates

2.2 Arbitrages

Let us suppose that initially each producer is aware only of three its own exchange rates. For instance, Food Producer knows only the rates

rF​A,rF​R,rF​M.subscript𝑟𝐹𝐴subscript𝑟𝐹𝑅subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀r_{FA},\quad r_{FR},\quad r_{FM}. (2.7)

For instance, let us suppose that Food Producer can make profit by first, exchanging one unit of Food for rF​Msubscript𝑟𝐹𝑀r_{FM} units of Medicine, and then by exchanging this Medicine for Arms. Mathematically this means that the product rF​M⋅rM​A⋅subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript𝑟𝑀𝐴r_{FM}\cdot r_{MA} is greater than rF​Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{FA}:

rF​M⋅rM​A>rF​A.⋅subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript𝑟𝑀𝐴subscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{FM}\cdot r_{MA}>r_{FA}. (2.8)

rF​An​e​w=rF​M⋅rM​A=rF​MrA​M.subscriptsuperscript𝑟𝑛𝑒𝑤𝐹𝐴⋅subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript𝑟𝑀𝐴subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript𝑟𝐴𝑀r^{new}_{FA}={r_{FM}}\cdot r_{MA}=\frac{r_{FM}}{r_{AM}}.

The principal distinction of the FARM-economy from the economy with only three producers (as described in Motivation) is that applying a single arbitrage procedure would not necessarily result in bringing the economy to a balance.

2.3 The Hypothesis

One can apply arbitrages from Table LABEL:tab1 sequentially in any order and to any initial exchange rates ℛℛ\mathcal{R}. A situation that we have in mind is the following. Suppose that there exists Arbiter who has access to the current ensemble ℛℛ\mathcal{R}. This Arbiter could provide information to the producers in any order he wants, thus activating the chain (or superposition) of corresponding arbitrages. The principal question is:

Question 1.

How powerful is Arbiter?

The short answer is: Arbiter is surprisingly powerful; possibly, Arbiter is almighty.

Let us explain at a more formal level what we mean.

For a finite chain of arbitrages 𝐀=𝒜1​…​𝒜n,𝐀subscript𝒜1…subscript𝒜𝑛{\bf A}=\mathcal{A}_{1}\ldots\mathcal{A}_{n}, and for a given ensemble ℛℛ\mathcal{R} of initial exchange rates, we denote by

ℛ​𝐀=ℛ​𝒜1​…​𝒜nℛ𝐀ℛsubscript𝒜1…subscript𝒜𝑛\mathcal{R}{\bf A}=\mathcal{R}\mathcal{A}_{1}\ldots\mathcal{A}_{n} (2.9)

the resulting ensemble of principal exchange rates. If ℛℛ\mathcal{R} is balanced, then ℛ​𝒜=ℛℛ𝒜ℛ\mathcal{R}{\mathcal{A}}=\mathcal{R} for any individual arbitrage, and therefore ℛ​𝐀=ℛℛ𝐀ℛ\mathcal{R}{\bf A}=\mathcal{R} for any chain (2.9). If, on the contrary, ℛℛ\mathcal{R} is not balanced, then different chains (2.9) of arbitrages could result at different balanced or unbalanced ensembles of principal exchange rates. Denote by S​(ℛ)𝑆ℛS(\mathcal{R}) the collection of the sets ℛ​𝐀ℛ𝐀\mathcal{R}{\bf A} related to all possible sequences (2.9). Denote also by Sb​a​l​(ℛ)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙ℛS^{bal}(\mathcal{R}) the subset of S​(ℛ)𝑆ℛS(\mathcal{R}), that includes only balanced exchange rates ensembles. Our principal observation is the following.

For a typical unbalanced ensemble ℛℛ\mathcal{R} the set Sb​a​l​(ℛ)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙ℛS^{bal}(\mathcal{R}) is unexpectedly reach; therefore Arbiter, who prescribes a particular sequence of arbitrages, is an unexpectedly powerful figure.

To avoid cumbersome notations and technical details when providing a rigorous formulation of this observation, we concentrate on the simplest example of the initial ensemble. Let us consider the ensemble

ℛα=(α⋅r¯F​A,r¯F​R,r¯F​M,r¯A​R,r¯A​M,r¯R​M),subscriptℛ𝛼⋅𝛼subscript¯𝑟𝐹𝐴subscript¯𝑟𝐹𝑅subscript¯𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript¯𝑟𝐴𝑅subscript¯𝑟𝐴𝑀subscript¯𝑟𝑅𝑀\mathcal{R}_{\alpha}=\left(\alpha\cdot\bar{r}_{FA},\ \bar{r}_{FR},\ \bar{r}_{FM},\ \bar{r}_{AR},\ \bar{r}_{AM},\ \bar{r}_{RM}\right), (2.10)

where α>1𝛼1\alpha>1 and ℛ¯¯ℛ\bar{\mathcal{R}} is a given balanced ensemble of principal exchange rates. The ensemble (2.10) is not balanced. A possible origination of the ensemble (2.10) may be commented as follows. Let us suppose that the underlying balanced rates

ℛ¯=(r¯F​A,r¯F​R,r¯F​M,r¯A​R,r¯A​M,r¯R​M)¯ℛsubscript¯𝑟𝐹𝐴subscript¯𝑟𝐹𝑅subscript¯𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript¯𝑟𝐴𝑅subscript¯𝑟𝐴𝑀subscript¯𝑟𝑅𝑀\bar{\mathcal{R}}=\left(\bar{r}_{FA},\ \bar{r}_{FR},\ \bar{r}_{FM},\ \bar{r}_{AR},\ \bar{r}_{AM},\ \bar{r}_{RM}\right) (2.11)

had been in operation up to a certain reference time moment 00. At this moment τ𝜏\tau the Food Producer has decided to increase his price for Arms by a factor α>1𝛼1\alpha>1. A natural specification of Question 1 is the following:

Question 2.

Proposition 2 in no way answers Question 2. This proposition, however, allows us to reformulate this question in a more “constructive” form:

Question 3.

How big is the set Sb​a​l​(ℛα)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙subscriptℛ𝛼S^{bal}(\mathcal{R}_{\alpha}), comparing with the collection Tαb​a​lsubscriptsuperscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑙𝛼T^{bal}_{\alpha} of all elements that satisfy restrictions imposed by Proposition 2?

The naive expectation would be that the set Sb​a​l​(ℛα)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙subscriptℛ𝛼S^{bal}(\mathcal{R}_{\alpha}), is finite and, at least for the values of α𝛼\alpha close to 1, all elements of Sb​a​l​(ℛα)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙subscriptℛ𝛼S^{bal}(\mathcal{R}_{\alpha}) are close to ℛ¯¯ℛ\bar{\mathcal{R}}. Hypothesis 1.

The set Sb​a​l​(ℛα)superscript𝑆𝑏𝑎𝑙subscriptℛ𝛼S^{bal}(\mathcal{R}_{\alpha}) coincides with Tαb​a​lsubscriptsuperscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑙𝛼T^{bal}_{\alpha}:

Loosely speaking, this hypothesis means that Arbiter is almighty.

3 Mathematical Background

3.1 Reformulation in the Linear Algebra Terms

Analysis of sequences of arbitrages in FARM-economy admits an elegant geometric interpretation, to be discussed in this section. Actually, we have used heavily this interpretation when inventing and proving results from Subsection 2.4 (although many proves can be eventually rewritten without explicit references to the geometrical interpretation). We also feel that this interpretation will be useful in understanding more complicated, and more realistic, mathematical models in economics.

We use, as an auxiliary tool, a somehow stronger arbitrage procedure. Let us begin with an example. Consider the combination (F​A​M)𝐹𝐴𝑀(FAM). For a given ℛℛ\mathcal{R} we define the Strong Arbitrage 𝒜^(F​A​M)​ℛsubscript^𝒜𝐹𝐴𝑀ℛ\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{(FAM)}\mathcal{R} as 𝒜F​A​Msubscript𝒜𝐹𝐴𝑀\mathcal{A}_{FAM} if the inequality (2.8) holds, and as 𝒜A​F​Msubscript𝒜𝐴𝐹𝑀\mathcal{A}_{AFM}, otherwise. Note that in both cases the result in terms of principal rates is the same: the rate rF​Asubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴r_{FA} is changed to rF​An​e​w=rF​MrA​M.superscriptsubscript𝑟𝐹𝐴𝑛𝑒𝑤subscript𝑟𝐹𝑀subscript𝑟𝐴𝑀r_{FA}^{new}=\frac{r_{FM}}{r_{AM}}.

The strong arbitrage 𝒜^(F​A​M)subscript^𝒜𝐹𝐴𝑀\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{(FAM)} is the second entry in Table LABEL:starbT of the possible 12 strong arbitrages. The meaning of a strong arbitrage is simple. This is just balancing a corresponding “sub-economy” (F​A​M)𝐹𝐴𝑀(FAM) by changing the exchange rate for a pair F⇆A.⇆𝐹𝐴F\leftrightarrows A.

3.4 Consequences

By inspection, the set ℙ=co​{±s1,±s2,±s3,±s4,±s5,±s6}ℙcoplus-or-minussubscript𝑠1plus-or-minussubscript𝑠2plus-or-minussubscript𝑠3plus-or-minussubscript𝑠4plus-or-minussubscript𝑠5plus-or-minussubscript𝑠6\mathbb{P}=\textrm{co}\left\{\pm s_{1},\pm s_{2},\pm s_{3},\pm s_{4},\pm s_{5},\pm s_{6}\right\} has a non-empty interior. It is a polyhedron, with six quadrilateral and eight triangular faces. This polyhedron is a usual (a little bit elongated) triangular orthobicupola, shown at Fig. 3.

We can consider this polyhedron ℙℙ\mathbb{P} as the unit ball in an auxiliary norm ∥⋅∥∗\|\cdot\|_{*}, in which ‖Gn‖∗≤1,n=1,2,…,12.formulae-sequencesubscriptnormsubscript𝐺𝑛1𝑛12…12\|G_{n}\|_{*}\leq 1,\quad n=1,2,\ldots,12. Thus, the set of matrices {Gn}subscript𝐺𝑛\{G_{n}\} is neutrally stable.

This implies that any product of matrices D𝐷D, and therefore any product of matrices B𝐵B has only eigenvectors which are equal either to 00 or to 111. In particular the spectral radius of any product is equal to 111. This proves both Proposition 6 and Proposition 4.

3.5 Links to the Asynchronous Systems Theory

In conclusion, we make three remarks which could be useful in investigation of systems with more than four producers.

  • •

    Construction of matrices Bnsubscript𝐵𝑛B_{n} may be interpreted as a special case of construction of mixtures of matrices in the asynchronous systems theory (see [1] or a short survey [5]). Convergence analysis for the product of matrices B𝐵B is analogous to analysis of absolute r𝑟r-asymptotic stability of asynchronous system. This problem is also similar to the problem of estimating the generalized (joint) spectral radius of a family of matrices consisting of all matrices Bnsubscript𝐵𝑛B_{n}.

  • •

    Since the matrices G𝐺G are integer, the convergence of long regular sequences to zero is similar to the well known mortality problem (see [4, 2, 3, 8]).

  • •

    In the case of matrices G𝐺G, the subspace of common fixed points of these matrices is trivial. Moreover, this set of matrices is irreducible: they do not have common invariant subspaces. Following [6, 7] one can find an explicit estimate for norms of all products of matrices from irreducible family. Furthermore, if all entries of the matrices are integer, the question whether any sufficiently long product would equal to zero is algorithmically solvable in a finite (may be very large, but still finite) number of operations.
